    projectMosaicRedirection: "🧩 Project Mosaic",
    nextPage: "Use the sections above to explore plain-language legal explanations, curated low-cost legal aid and community support organizations, and the ongoing initiatives of Project Mosaic. This space will continue expanding as new verified resources and tools are added.",
    
    //Simplified Legal Frameworks//
    simplifiedTitle: "Simplified Legal Frameworks",
    simplifiedSection: "This section provides plain-language explanations of key immigration-related legal rights and processes in the United States. The goal is to help individuals understand common situations they may face and know where to seek trusted help.",
    know: "Know Your Basic Rights in the U.S.",
    firstRight: "You have the right to remain silent when questioned by immigration or law enforcement.",
    seccondRight: "You have the right to refuse a search of your home unless officers have a valid warrant signed by a judge.",
    thirdRight: "You have the right to speak with an attorney before signing any documents.",
    fourthRight: "You do not have to disclose your immigration status to local police in most situations.",
    fifthRight: "If you are detained by immigration, you have the right to contact your consulate.",
    important: "<strong>Important:</strong> Never present false documents or provide false information to immigration officials.",
    pieceOfAdvice: "If Immigration Officers Come to Your Door",
    bulletPointOne: "Stay calm and do not open the door.",
    bulletPointTwo: "Ask officers to show the warrant through a window or slide it under the door.",
    bulletPointThree: "Check that the warrant is signed by a judge and has your correct name and address.",
    bulletPointFour: "If there is no valid judicial warrant, you may refuse entry.",
    bulletPointFive: "Do not sign anything without speaking to a qualified attorney.",
    commonSolutions: "Common Immigration Relief Pathways",
    descCommonSolutions: "Some immigrants in the United States may qualify for forms of humanitarian or family-based relief depending on their situation. Each case is different, but common pathways include:",
    familyPetitions: "<strong>Family-based petitions</strong> — through qualifying U.S. citizen or permanent resident relatives.",
    asylumSolution: "<strong>Asylum</strong> — for individuals who fear persecution in their home country.", 
    uVisa: "<strong>U Visa</strong> — for victims of certain crimes who assist law enforcement.",
    tVisa: "<strong>T Visa</strong> — for survivors of human trafficking.",
    specialImmigrant: "<strong>Special Immigrant Juvenile Status (SIJS)</strong> — for certain undocumented minors.",
    requirements: "Eligibility requirements are complex. Always confirm with a trusted legal provider.",
    warningToAvoid: "⚠️ Avoid Immigration Scams (“Notario” Fraud)",
    pointOne: "In the U.S., a “notario” is <strong>not</strong> an immigration lawyer.",
    pointTwo: "Only licensed attorneys or DOJ-accredited representatives can give legal advice.",
    pointThree: "Be cautious of anyone who guarantees fast results or special connections.",
    pointFour: "Always request written contracts and receipts.",
    seekHelp: "When to Seek Legal Help",
    howToSeekHelp: "You should try to speak with a qualified immigration attorney or accredited representative if you:",
    papers: "Receive immigration court papers",
    detainment: "Are detained by immigration authorities",
    benefits: "Are considering applying for immigration benefits",
    history: "Have prior removal or deportation orders",
    whatNext: "Visit the <strong>Community Resource Hub</strong> dropdown for verified, low-cost legal service providers.",
    communityResourceNext: "🧭 Community Resource Hub",
    disclaimer: "<strong>Disclaimer:</strong> This information is for educational purposes only and is not legal advice. Immigration law is complex and changes frequently. Consult a qualified attorney or accredited representative for advice about your specific situation.",
    
